surveys.narrative: WALLEYE: THE 1996 CATCH OF WALLEYE PER EXPERIMENTAL GILLNET LIFT WAS 9.5. THIS CATCH WAS CONSIDERABLY HIGHER THAN THE 1983-96 AVERAGE (7.6/LIFT) AND THE THIRD HIGHEST SINCE ANNUAL SAMPLING BEGAN (1983). THE 1994 AND 1995 WALLEYE YEAR CLASSES COMPRISED A LARGE PERCENTAGE OF SAMPLED WALLEYE CAUSING CATCH RATES TO INCREASE AND AVERAGE LENGTH AND WEIGHT TO DECLINE (13.1 INCHES AND 0.9 POUNDS). PRELIMINARY FINDINGS INDICATE THE 1996 YEAR CLASS MAY ALSO BE STRONG. IF THIS IS THE CASE, UPON RECRUITMENT TO THE GILLNET, NEAR RECORD GILLNET CATCH RATES CAN BE EXPECTED. THE LOW CATCH RATES AND HIGH AVERGE LENGTH AND WEIGHT IN 1993 (4.6/LIFT; 15.6 INCHES AND 1.5 POUNDS) AND 1994 (4.9/LIFT; 16.7 INCHES AND 1.8 POUNDS) WAS A RESULT OF POOR REPRODUCTION AND/OR RECRUITMENT OF THE 1989, 1990, 1992 AND 1993 YEAR CLASSES. IN 1989 AND 1990, REPRODUCTION WAS SUPPRESSED BY THE EXCEPTIONALLY STRONG 1988 YEAR CLASS. AS A RESULT OF RECORD COLD SUMMERS, POOR PRODUCTION OF FORAGE CAUSED THE 1992 AND 1993 WALLEYE YEARS CLASSES TO FAIL.LEECH LAKE ANGLERS AND RESORT OWNERS REPORTED EXCELLENT WALLEYE ANGLING, ESPECIALLY FOR LARGE WALLEYE, DURING THE EARLY PART OF THE 1996 OPEN WATER SEASON. AS IN 1995, ANGLERS WERE DELIGHTED WITH THE AVERAGE SIZE OF WALLEYE. HOWEVER, MANY EXPRESSED CONCERN ABOUT FEW SMALL WALLEYE BEING CAUGHT. THIS CONCERN QUICKLY DISAPPEARED IN EARLY JULY WHEN THE 1994 WALLEYE YEAR CLASS BECAME LARGE ENOUGH TO BE CAUGHT BY ANGLERS. NEAR THE MIDDLE OF AUGUST THESE WALLEYE BEGAN ATTAINING SIZES ACCEPTABLE TO THE AVERAGE ANGLER (12-14 INCHES) AND LIMITS OF WALLEYE BECAME COMMON THROUGH FREEZE-UP.FOR 1997, ANGLERS SHOULD EXPECT GOOD WALLEYE ACTION. THE 1994 YEAR CLASS IS ACCEPTABLE TO MOST ANGLERS AND IS PRESENT IN LARGE NUMBERS. NEAR MID-AUGUST, THE STRONG 1995 YEAR CLASS WILL ALSO BEGIN TO ATTAIN SIZES ACCEPTABLE TO ANGLERS. THESE TWO YEAR CLASSES COUPLED WITH STILL ABUNDANT 1985, 1988 AND 1991 YEAR-CLASSES WILL PROVIDE AMPLE WALLEYE ANGLING OPPORTUNITIES ON LEECH LAKE. THESE OPPORTUNITIES WILL INCLUDE BOTH QUANTITY AND QUALITY OF WALLEYE.NORTHERN PIKE: THE 1996 CATCH OF NORTHERN PIKE PER EXPERIMENTAL GILLNET SET WAS 4.8, SLIGHTLY HIGHER THAN THE 1983-1996 AVERAGE (4.7 NORTHERN PIKE PER SET). SAMPLED NORTHERN PIKE AVERAGED 20.8 INCHES AND 2.3 POUNDS. THIS AVERAGE DECLINED CONSIDERABLY FROM THE 1995 SAMPLING WHICH WAS THE HIGHEST EVER RECORDED (22.8 INCHES AND 3.1 POUNDS). THE OVERALL AVERAGE LENGTH AND WEIGHT OF NORTHERN PIKE, SINCE THE BEGINNING OF THE LARGE LAKE MONITORING PROGRAM (1983), IS 21.1 INCHES AND 2.3 POUNDS. OF THE 174 NORTHERN PIKE SAMPLED IN 1996, 57 PERCENT WERE FEMALE ND 43 PERCENT WERE MALE. ANGLING FOR NORTHERN PIKE WAS AGAIN REPORTED TO BE GOOD THIS PAST YEAR. DURING THE MUSKY INC. INTERNATIONAL MUSKELLUNGE TOURNAMENT, WHICH WAS HELD IN EARLY SEPTEMBER, MORE NORTHERN PIKE LARGER THAN 36 INCHES WERE REPORTED FROM LEECH LAKE THAN ALL OTHER LAKES INCLUDED IN THE TOURNAMENT.YELLOW PERCH: THE 1996 CATCH OF YELLOW PERCH PER EXPERIMENTAL GILL NET SET WAS 25.6. THIS CATCH IS THE FOURTH HIGHEST EVER RECORDED. THE LOWEST CATCH OCCURRED IN 1986 (13.2 YELLOW PERCH PER SET) AND THE HIGHEST IN 1995 (37.7 YELLOW PERCH PER SET). THE 1996 AVERAGE LENGTH OF SAMPLED YELLOW PERCH WAS 7.7 INCHES. THIS AVERAGE HAS CONTINUED TO INCREASE SINCE 1992 WHEN THE STRONG 1989 YEAR CLASS BEGAN TO BE RECRUITED TO THE GILLNET. AS IN MOST PREVIOUS SAMPLING, THE AVERAGE WEIGHT OF SAMPLED YELLOW PERCH WAS 0.2 POUNDS. NO YEAR HAS DEVIATED MORE THAN 0.1 POUNDS FROM THIS AVERAGE. SEX WAS DETERMINED FOR 845 OF THE 923 YELLOW PERCH SAMPLED. OF THOSE, 65 PERCENT WERE FEMALES AND 35 PERCENT WERE MALES. FEMALE YELLOW PERCH HAVE CONSISTENTLY OUTNUMBERED MALES BY APPROXIMATELY 2:1. THIS ANOMALY IS AN EFFECT OF GILL NET SELECTIVITY FOR FEMALE YELLOW PERCH RATHER THAN A DESCRIPTION OF THE SEX DISTRIBUTION OF YELLOW PERCH IN LEECH LAKE.ANGLERS ENJOYED GOOD SUCCESS WHILE ANGLING FOR YELLOW PERCH THIS PAST YEAR. BEST SUCCESS OCCURRED FROM OPENING OF FISHING TO MID-JUNE AND FROM MID-AUGUST TO NEAR FREEZE-UP. THE EARLY SEASON SUCCESS COULD BE PARTIALLY ATTRIBUTED TO THE LATE ICE-OUT (MAY 11) WHICH DELAYED SPAWNING UNTIL AFTER OPENING DAY OF FISHING WHEN MORE ANGLERS ARE ON THE WATER. JUST BEFORE AND AFTER SPAWNING, YELLOW PERCH ARE OFTEN READILY CAUGHT BY ANGLERS. LOCAL CONSERVATION OFFICERS REPORTED GOOD YELLOW PERCH SUCCESS FROM MID-AUGUST TO NEAR FREEZE-UP.CISCO: THE 1996 CATCH OF CISCO PER EXPERIMENTAL GILL NET SET WAS 4.7. THIS CATCH IS 3.3 FISH LOWER THAN THE 1983-96 AVERAGE (8.0 CISCO PER SET) BUT CONSIDERABLY HIGHER THAN THE LOWEST CATCH EVER RECORDED (1989; 2.1 PER SET). THE HIGHEST CATCH PER SET OCCURRED IN 1987 (18.5 PER NET). GILLENT CATCH RATES FOR CISCO DISPLAY CONSIDERABLE VARIABILITY FROM YEAR TO YEAR AND DO NOT APPEAR TO BE A RELIABLE INDICATOR OF ABUNDANCE. THE AVERAGE LENGTH AND WEIGHT (11.8 INCHES AND 0.6 POUNDS) OF CISCO SAMPLED DURING 1996 WERE SIMILAR TO OVERALL AVERAGES (10.7 INCHES AND 0.6 POUNDS). THE LARGEST DEVIATIONS FROM THESE OVERALL AVERAGES OCCURRED IN 1984 (13.4 INCHES AND 1.0 POUNDS) AND 1990 (8.5 INCHES AND 0.2 POUNDS).

Leech Lake is the third largest lake entirely within the boundaries of Minnesota and has approximately 112,000 surface acres. The lake is geographically located in three glacial zones and has an irregular shape with many large and small bays. The deepest area of the lake is located in Walker Bay where depths reach around 150 feet deep. Approximately 80% of the lake is less than 35 feet deep. Similar to other large lakes in Minnesota, the fish community is dominated by species in the perch and pike families. Walleye, northern pike, and muskellunge are the primary predator species, whereas yellow perch and cisco are principal forage species. Leech Lake is well known among anglers for its excellent walleye, northern pike, and muskellunge fishing. Each year, anglers spend approximately 1.2 million hours on Leech Lake during the open-water fishing season. Summer angling pressure on Leech Lake has increased approximately 47% since the mid 1960's. This trend of increasing angling pressure has been occurring statewide. Although angling pressure has been increasing through time, total harvest has remained relatively stable. Consequently, today's angler's fishing success is somewhat less than that of the past creating a perception of a declining sport fishery. Walleye: The 2000 catch of walleye per experimental gill net set was 5.9 which is somewhat less than the 1983-2000 average of 7.7 walleye per set. Historically, catch rates have ranged from 4.6 walleye/set (1993) to 13.4 walleye/set (1988). Walleye sampled in experimental gill nets ranged in length from 7.0 to 30.0 inches with an average length of 15.3 inches. As a result of consistent recruitment of walleye year classes between 1994-1997, good numbers of fish greater than 15 inches in length should provide quality angling opportunities in 2001. Northern Pike: The 2000 catch of northern pike per experimental gill net was 5.0. Since 1983, northern pike gill net catch rates have been stable ranging from 3.6 pike/set (1993) to 6.2 pike/set (1995). Northern pike sampled in experimental gill nets in 2000 ranged in length from 10.0 to 37.5 inches with an average length of 21.1 inches. Muskellunge: In 2000, two muskellunge were sampled in experimental gill nets. Muskellunge are typically low in abundance and grow to sizes which are not effectively sampled with gill nets. Several 50+ inch muskellunge were reported caught by anglers in 2000. Data collected during the 1999 fishing season suggests it takes the average musky angler approximately 37 hours to catch a muskellunge. All anglers interviewed during our 1999 creel survey released their muskellunge back into Leech Lake which illustrates a strong catch and release ethic among musky anglers. The average size of angler caught muskellunge of legal size (>40 inches) was 43.3 inches. Yellow Perch: The 2000 catch of yellow perch per experimental gill net set was 21.2 which is comparable to the 1983-2000 average of 22.4 perch per set. Historically, yellow perch gill net catch rates have ranged from 13.5 perch/set (1983) to 37.7 perch/set (1995). In 2000, yellow perch sampled in gill nets ranged in length from 5.2 to 12.5 inches with an average length of 7.6 inches. Cisco: The 2000 catch of cisco per experimental gill net set was 2.7. Since 1983, gill net catch rates for cisco have varied considerably ranging from 2.1 cisco/set (1989) to 18.5 cisco/set (1987). Cisco sampled in gill nets in 2000 ranged in length from 7.3 to 16.8 inches with an average length of 11.7 inches. Leech Lake also provides quality angling opportunities for largemouth bass, black crappie, and sunfish in several shallow vegetated bays. These species are not effectively sampled with gill nets. To promote and maintain a healthy fish population, pollution and other inputs need to be controlled. Fish habitat is directly affected by water quality. Nutrient, sediment and other waste inputs can drastically alter the chemical and physical components of Leech Lake. Best management practices should be employed when developing a shoreline. Careless development within the watershed and the loss of upland and aquatic vegetation can accelerate the natural aging of a lake. It is paramount to maintain the current water quality of Leech Lake through watershed management to preserve this fishery for future generations to enjoy. Scientists have recently identified a new yellow perch parasite found in Leech Lake and the Eagle River Chain of Lakes in Wisconsin. This microscopic parasite, Heterosporis, is rare in sportfish and causes the flesh to have a "cooked" or "freezer burned" appearance. Although infected muscles cells reduce the quality and change the texture of the fillet, there is no evidence that an infected perch is unsafe to eat. Most people choose to discard affected portions of the fillets. To help prevent the spread of this parasite, infected fish remains should not be thrown back into the water, boat exteriors and other equipment should be thoroughly dried, and live wells and bilges should be disinfected with bleach before moving to other bodies of water.

Leech Lake is the third largest lake entirely within the boundaries of Minnesota and has approximately 112,000 surface acres. The lake is geographically located in three glacial zones and has an irregular shape with many large and small bays. The deepest area of the lake is located in Walker Bay where depths reach around 150 feet deep. Approximately 80% of the lake is less than 35 feet deep. Similar to other large lakes in Minnesota, the fish community is dominated by species in the perch and pike families. Walleye, northern pike, and muskellunge are the primary predator species, while yellow perch and cisco are principal forage species. Leech Lake is well known among anglers for its walleye, northern pike, and muskellunge fishing.

Walleye: The 2006 catch of walleye per experimental gill net set was 7.1 which is near the 1983-2006 average of 7.3 walleye per set and higher than last year. The increase in catch rate in 2006 is due to the 2005 year class recruiting to the gear. After aging all walleye caught in fall test nets, 96 age 1 walleye were sampled, the highest number since 1998. Historical gill net catch rates have ranged from 4.6 walleye/set (1993) to 13.4 walleye/set (1988). Walleye sampled in experimental gill nets ranged in length from 6.2 to 25.2 inches with an average length of 15.7 inches. Catch rates were higher in the main lake (8.7 walleye/set) than in the western bays (5.1 walleye/set).

Northern Pike: The 2006 catch of northern pike per experimental gill net was similar to previous catches at 4.0 per set. Since 1983, northern pike gill net catch rates have been stable ranging from 3.6 pike/set (1993) to 6.2 pike/set (1995). Northern pike sampled in experimental gill nets in 2006 ranged in length from 9.3 to 32.7 inches with an average length of 22.4 inches. RSD-28 was 9, which is above the long-term average (8).

Muskellunge: In 2006, one 26.3 inch muskellunge was sampled in experimental gill nets. Muskellunge are typically low in abundance and grow to sizes which are not effectively sampled with gill nets.

Yellow Perch: The 2006 catch of yellow perch per experimental gill net set was 20.5 which is greater than last years catch rate of 12.9. Historically, yellow perch gill net catch rates have ranged from last years low catch rate to 37.7 perch/set (1995), averaging 21.1 perch/set. The main lake catch rate was 2.7 times higher than last years catch rate (7.8/set). The increase in yellow perch abundance in the main lake is likely the result of good natural reproduction in recent years and efforts to reduce the population of double-crested cormorants in 2005 and 2006. In 2006, yellow perch sampled in gill nets ranged in length from 4.2 to 12.0 inches with an average length of 7.1 inches. Of the 737 yellow perch sampled with gill nets, 3.8% were >10 inches. This percentage is one-half of last years value, however, the decrease is due to the increased catch of small yellow perch. The actual number of yellow perch sampled >10 inches was 28, up from last year (24).
Cisco: The 2006 catch of cisco per experimental gill net set was 0.6, the lowest value observed during the large lake program. Since 1983, gill net catch rates for cisco have varied considerably ranging from this years low to 18.5 cisco/set (1987). The catch of cisco may have been impacted by this years summer kill. Cisco sampled in gill nets in 2006 ranged in length from 8.1 to 13.3 inches with an average length of 9.9 inches.

Leech Lake also provides quality angling opportunities for largemouth bass, black crappie, and sunfish in several shallow vegetated bays. These species are not effectively sampled with gill nets. Anglers report occasional catches of smallmouth bass around Bear and Pelican Islands.

Due to recent trends in walleye and yellow perch catch data, a five-year action plan was developed for Leech Lake in 2004. This plan aims to increase the abundance and create a more stable size structure for these two species. Management activities include: restrictive regulations for walleye, science-based cormorant control, walleye stocking and an increased focus on habitat protection. Habitat protection includes watershed-level land management as fish habitat is directly affected by the water quality that enter the lake via runoff. It is paramount to maintain the current water quality of Leech Lake through watershed management to preserve this fishery for future generations to enjoy.

Leech Lake is the third largest lake entirely within Minnesotas boundaries and covers approximately 112,000 surface acres. The lake is geographically located in three glacial zones and has an irregular shape with many large and small bays. The deepest area of the lake is located in Walker Bay where depths reach around 150 feet deep. Approximately 80% of the lake is less than 35 feet deep. Similar to other large lakes in Minnesota, the fish community is dominated by species in the perch and pike families. Walleye, northern pike, and muskellunge are the primary predator species, while yellow perch and cisco are principal forage species. Leech Lake is well known among anglers for its walleye, northern pike, and muskellunge fishing.

Walleye: Since the Large Lake Program began in 1983, walleye gillnet catch rates have ranged from 4.6 fish/net (1993) to 13.4 fish/net (1988). The 2007 catch of walleye per experimental gillnet set was 13.1 fish/net, the second highest on record, and is well above the 1983-2007 average of 7.5 fish/net. The increase in the walleye gillnet catch rate is due to the large year classes of walleyes produced in 2005 and 2006; 61% of walleyes caught during the 2007 gillnet survey were from these two year classes. Walleyes sampled in experimental gillnets ranged in length from 6.7 to 26.3 inches with an average length of 14.8 inches. Gillnet catch rates were higher in the main lake (18.4 fish/net) than in the western bays (6.6 fish/net). Reports from anglers have been good across the entire lake since the 2007 opener and a special creel survey is scheduled for summer 2008.

Northern Pike: The 2007 catch of northern pike per experimental gillnet was 5.9 fish/net. Northern pike gillnet catch rates have remained relatively stable since 1983, ranging from 3.6 fish/net (1993) to 6.2 fish/net (1995) with an average of 4.8 fish/net. Northern pike captured in 2007 gillnet sets ranged in length from 12.1 inches to 35.1 inches with an average length of 23.1 inches.

Muskellunge: Only one muskellunge of 17.7 inches was sampled in experimental gillnet sets during 2007. Muskellunge are typically low in abundance and exceed sizes that are effectively sampled with gillnets.

Yellow Perch: Gillnet catch rates of yellow perch have ranged from 20.5 fish/net (2005) to 37.7 fish/net (1995). The 2007 catch rate of yellow perch in experimental gillnet sets was 36.9 fish/net. This is well above the catch rates observed in 2006 (20.5 fish/net) and 2005 (12.9 fish/net) and is also above the 1983-2007 average of 21.7 fish/net. The increase in yellow perch abundance, particularly in the main lake, is likely the result of good natural reproduction in recent years as well as efforts to reduce the double-crested cormorant population on Leech Lake. Yellow perch sampled in 2007 gillnet sets ranged in length from 4.6 inches to 11.9 inches. Of the 1,326 total yellow perch caught, 29% were 8 inches and longer and 6% were 10 inches and longer; both of these proportions are anticipated to increase as young perch continue to grow and reach harvestable sizes.

Cisco: The 2007 catch rate of cisco per experimental gillnet set was 4.0 fish/net. Gillnet catch rates of cisco have varied considerable, ranging from 0.6 fish/net (2006) to 18.5 fish/net (1987), and the 1983-2007 average is 5.6 fish/net. Warmer summers resulting in summer kills have probably been the source of cisco catch rates remaining below average since 1995.

Leech Lake also provides quality angling opportunities for largemouth bass, black crappie, and sunfishes in shallow, vegetated bays. These species are not effectively sampled with gillnets. Anglers also occasionally report catches of smallmouth bass around Bear and Pelican islands.

Leech Lake is the third largest lake entirely within the boundaries of Minnesota and has approximately 112,000 surface acres. The lake is geographically located in three glacial zones and has an irregular shape with many large and small bays. The deepest area of the lake is located in Walker Bay where depths reach around 150 feet deep. Approximately 80% of the lake is less than 35 feet deep. Similar to other large lakes in Minnesota, the fish community is dominated by species in the perch and pike families. Walleye, northern pike, and muskellunge are the primary predator species, while yellow perch and cisco serve as the principal forage. Leech Lake is well known among anglers as a tremendous multi-species fishery, including excellent fishing opportunities for walleye, yellow perch, northern pike, muskellunge, largemouth bass, sunfish, and black crappie.

Leech Lake has been surveyed annually with standardized assessments since 1983. Establishment of long-term data sets on Leech Lake and Minnesota's other large walleye lakes allow biologists to compare current observations against historical averages. These long-term data sets can also provide insight into other lakes having similar physical and biological properties that are not sampled as frequently. Population metrics for a particular species, such as the highs and lows in gill net catch rates or the growth rates of fish, are constantly changing as they move from one extreme of their observed normal range to the other, much like a pendulum. While highs and lows are normal and rarely sustained past one year, consecutive observations at either extreme can be indicative of changes to an ecosystem. These may include exotic species introductions, shifts in habitat availability and/or quality, beneficial or adverse environmental conditions, and increased or decreased competition for resources between species or among year classes of the same species or among several species with similar requirements. Regardless, it is important to remember that all populations of flora and fauna fluctuate dramatically and that this natural variability is strongly influenced by the changing environment in which they live as well as the other species of plants and animals they share it with.

This report primarily addresses the 2010 Leech Lake fishery assessment. The 2007-2009 assessments of the Leech Lake fishery determined that all management goals outlined in the 2005-2010 action plan had been met or exceeded (Schultz 2008a, 2008b). Fishing quality on Leech Lake, indexed by targeting angler catch rates, improved significantly from the historic lows observed during 2005 to record highs during the 2008 open water season (Schultz 2009). Recent surveys have indicated substantial improvements to the walleye population and its fishery over the course of a few years. The completion and thorough evaluation of these efforts will refine current management strategies on Leech Lake as well as identify the needs for new ones.

The MN DNR convened a citizen input committee (Leech Lake Advisory Committee; LLAC) comprised of stakeholders representing local and statewide interests in Leech Lake management. This group outlined walleye population management objectives and actions, including double-crested cormorant control, the walleye regulation, and walleye fry stocking (LLAC 2010). These recommendations were incorporated into DNR's Leech Lake Management Plan, 2011-2015 (Schultz 2010a). These management goals, where appropriate, are referenced in this report.

The current protected slot walleye regulation (PSL) on Leech Lake (18-26" walleye must be immediately released; possession limit of 4, one of which may be longer than 26") was reviewed and compared to other regulation options (Schultz and Staples 2010a). Public comment on proposed regulation changes was solicited during October, 2010. The majority of public input supported maintaining the regulation through 2015, though some comments expressed consideration for a more liberal length limit that adjusts with measures of spawner biomass. Therefore, if measures of spawner biomass exceed 2.0 lbs/acre during two consecutive years, DNR will consider adjusting the regulation to a 20-26" PSL, bag of 4, one fish over 26" allowed in possession to begin the ensuing season based on current information.

Aquatic invasive species currently found in Leech Lake include rusty crayfish, heterosporosis, curly-leaf pondweed, Eurasian watermilfoil, purple loosestrife, and banded mystery snail. Currently invasive plant species are not widely distributed within Leech Lake. Other aquatic invasive species are increasing in prevalence throughout Minnesota and pose a likely risk. Anglers and boaters alike are encouraged to properly dispose of bait in the trash, to drain all water from bait containers, livewells, and watercraft, and properly inspect and remove all vegetation from the watercraft, anchor, and trailer when leaving a lake.

Walleye: Since the Large Lake Program began in 1983, walleye gillnet catch rates have ranged from 4.6 fish/net (1993) to 13.4 fish/net (1988). The 2010 catch of walleye per experimental gillnet set was 7.86 fish/net and remains above the 1983-2010 average of 7.6 fish/net. The improvements in the walleye population can be largely attributed to above-average year classes of walleye produced during 2005-2008. Walleye sampled in experimental gillnets ranged in length from 6 to 25 inches. Observed median lengths of the 2009, 2008, and 2007 year classes were approximately 10, 13, and 16 inches TL, respectively.

Statistics from the 2010 creel survey described another good walleye angling season on Leech Lake. Walleye were caught at a rate of 0.222 fish/hour and harvested at a rate of 0.091 fish/hour across all anglers. Anglers specifically targeting walleye caught fish at a rate of 0.645 walleye/hour and harvested fish at a rate of 0.197 walleye/hour. These statistics, in particular the targeting catch and harvest rates, are comparable to estimates collected during the 1990's.

Northern Pike: The 2010 gillnet catch rate of northern pike was 4.08 fish/net. Northern pike gillnet catch rates have remained relatively stable since 1983, ranging from 3.6 fish/net (1993) to 6.2 fish/net (1995) with an average of 4.8 fish/net. Northern pike captured in 2010 gillnet sets ranged in length from 8 to 33 inches.

Anglers targeting northern pike during 2010 caught pike at a rate of 0.755 fish/hour and harvested pike at a rate of 0.247 fish/hour. The average length of harvested northern pike during 2010 was 23.13 inches.

Muskellunge: Only two muskellunge were sampled in experimental gillnet sets during 2010. Muskellunge are typically low in abundance and exceed sizes effectively sampled with gillnets.

Muskie anglers averaged 0.025 fish/hour, or 1 fish/50 angler-hours, during the 2010 fishing season. This is double the 2009 statistic and above the long-term average for targeting anglers (0.018 fish/hour). Catch rates were highest during July and August.

Yellow Perch: Gillnet catch rates of yellow perch have ranged from 12.9 fish/net (2005) to 37.7 fish/net (1995). The 2010 catch rate of yellow perch in experimental gillnet sets was 24.31 fish/net. This is above the 1983-2010 average of 22.1 fish/net. Yellow perch sampled in 2010 gillnet sets ranged in length from 4 inches to 12 inches. Of the total perch caught, 39% were 8 inches and longer and 11% were 10 inches and longer; both of these proportions have increased during recent years.

Anglers targeting yellow perch averaged a catch rate of 8.188 perch/hour and a harvest rate of 2.100 perch/hour during 2010. Catch and harvest rates were highest during September.

Cisco: The 2010 catch rate of cisco per experimental gillnet set was 5.94 fish/net and is above the long-term average of 5.66 fish/net. Gillnet catch rates of cisco have varied considerable, ranging from 0.6 fish/net (2006) to 18.5 fish/net (1987). Warmer summers causing summer kills have probably been the reason for cisco catch rates remaining below average since 1995. Strong year classes were produced in recent years and their extended persistence in the absence of summer kill events is presumed to be the cause of increased catch rates.

Careless development within the watershed and the loss of upland and aquatic vegetation can accelerate the natural aging of a lake. Humans have had dramatic impacts on fish populations by degrading or destroying habitat necessary for successful reproduction, growth, and survival. In particular, lakeshores are highly sensitive areas that are vital to the overall health of our lakes. Terrestrial vegetation provides habitat for birds, mammals, and amphibians and buffers lakes from runoff that carry chemicals and sediment. Near-shore aquatic vegetation provides protection and food for the early life-stages of some species, such as walleye, and serves as year-round habitat for others, such as bluegill and largemouth bass. Due to recent trends in yellow perch and walleye catch data, a five-year action plan was initiated in 2005. Action plan objectives were to increase the relative abundance and to stabilize the population size structure of these two species. Management activities used to meet these objectives have included more restrictive regulations for walleye, cormorant control, walleye stocking, and an increased focus on habitat protection. The annual fishery survey using experimental gill nets was completed by the Walker Area Fisheries office, MN DNR, between 1 September and 12 September 2008. A summary of trawling data, which has been completed annually during August and is used to index the relative abundance of young-of-year (YOY) walleye, is also included.

Walleye: Since the Large Lake Program began in 1983, walleye gillnet catch rates have ranged from 4.6 fish/net (1993) to 13.4 fish/net (1988). The 2008 catch of walleye per experimental gillnet set was 9.1 fish/net, well above the 1983-2008 average of 7.5 fish/net. The increase in the walleye gillnet catch rate is due to the large year classes of walleyes produced during 2005, 2006, and 2007; 79% of walleye caught during the 2008 gillnet survey were from these three year classes. Walleye sampled in experimental gillnets ranged in length from 8.9 to 26.0 inches with an average length of 15.5 inches. Gillnet catch rates were higher in the main lake (12.3 fish/net) than in the western bays (5.1 fish/net).

Statistics from the 2008 creel survey described one of the best walleye angling seasons ever recorded on Leech Lake. Walleye were caught at a rate of 0.278 fish/hour and harvested at a rate of 0.115 fish/hour across all anglers; anglers specifically targeting walleye caught fish at a rate of 1.064 walleye/hour and harvested fish at a rate of 0.459 walleye/hour. These statistics, in particular the targeting catch and harvest rates, are among the highest ever observed on Leech Lake. For comparison, respective walleye catch and harvest rates for targeting anglers were higher on Leech during 2008 than during 2007 on Mille Lacs (0.391 and 0.129 fish/hour), Lake of the Woods (0.550 and 0.290 fish/hour), and Winnibigoshish (0.545 and 0.229 fish/hour).

Northern pike gillnet catch rates have remained relatively stable since 1983, ranging from 3.6 fish/net (1993) to 6.2 fish/net (1995) with an average of 4.8 fish/net. Northern pike captured in 2008 gillnet sets ranged in length from 8.5 inches to 33.5 inches with an average length of 22.3 inches.

Anglers targeting northern pike during 2008 caught pike at a rate of 0.881 fish/hour and harvested pike at a rate of 0.339 fish/hour. Similar to targeting catch rates for walleye, statistics for Leech were higher than similar observations on Mille Lacs, Lake of the Woods, and Winnibigoshish during 2007.

2002 LEECH LAKE STATUS Leech Lake is the third largest lake entirely within the boundaries of Minnesota and has approximately 112,000 surface acres. The lake is geographically located in three glacial zones and has an irregular shape with many large and small bays. The deepest area of the lake is located in Walker Bay where depths reach around 150 feet deep. Approximately 80% of the lake is less than 35 feet deep. Similar to other large lakes in Minnesota, the fish community is dominated by species in the perch and pike families. Walleye, northern pike, and muskellunge are the primary predator species, while yellow perch and cisco are principal forage species. Leech Lake is well known among anglers for its excellent walleye, northern pike, and muskellunge fishing. Each year, anglers spend approximately 1.2 million hours on Leech Lake during the open-water fishing season. Summer angling pressure on Leech Lake has increased approximately 47% since the mid 1960's. This trend of increasing angling pressure has been occurring statewide. Although angling pressure has been increasing through time, total harvest has remained relatively stable. Consequently, today's angler's fishing success is somewhat less than that of the past creating a perception of a declining sport fishery. Walleye: The 2002 catch of walleye per experimental gill net set was 6.2 which is below the 1983-2002 average of 7.6 walleye per set. Historically, catch rates have ranged from 4.6 walleye/set (1993) to 13.4 walleye/set (1988). Walleye sampled in experimental gill nets ranged in length from 6.5 to 25.4 inches with an average length of 15.7 inches. The highest catch rate for walleye occurred off of Sugar Point (18 walleye). Northern Pike: The 2002 catch of northern pike per experimental gill net was identical to last year at 5.3. Since 1983, northern pike gill net catch rates have been stable ranging from 3.6 pike/set (1993) to 6.2 pike/set (1995). Northern pike sampled in experimental gill nets in 2002 ranged in length from 9.1 to 34.2 inches with an average length of 20.3 inches. Muskellunge: In 2002, no muskellunge were sampled in experimental gill nets. Muskellunge are typically low in abundance and grow to sizes which are not effectively sampled with gill nets. Muskie anglers enjoyed one of the best seasons in years. The five day Muskie Pike Derby tournament registered 39 muskies (all fish were released), with an average length of 44.7 inches . All anglers interviewed during the 1999 creel survey released their muskellunge back into Leech Lake which illustrates a strong catch and release ethic among musky anglers. Yellow Perch: The 2002 catch of yellow perch per experimental gill net set was 20.5 which is near the 1983-2002 average of 22.0 perch per set and up 33 percent from 2001. Historically, yellow perch gill net catch rates have ranged from 13.5 perch/set (1983) to 37.7 perch/set (1995). In 2002, yellow perch sampled in gill nets ranged in length from 4.3 to 12.6 inches with an average length of 6.8 inches. Of the 738 yellow perch sampled with gill nets, 6.4% were >10 inches. The 47 yellow perch sampled >10 inches is the lowest number sampled since 1987. Sampled yellow perch were also examined for the presence of Heterosporis. Of the fish examined, 37 are believed infected which correlates to approximately 6.7 percent. If confirmed, this is approximately double the 2001 infection rate yet below levels found in 2000. Tissue samples were taken from suspect fish to confirm the presence of the parasite. Cisco: The 2002 catch of cisco per experimental gill net set was 1.6. Since 1983, gill net catch rates for cisco have varied considerably ranging from the last year's low of 1.3 cisco/set to 18.5 cisco/set (1987). Cisco sampled in gill nets in 2002 ranged in length from 6.8 to 17.1 inches with an average length of 11.0 inches. Leech Lake also provides quality angling opportunities for largemouth bass, black crappie, and sunfish in several shallow vegetated bays. These species are not effectively sampled with gill nets. One smallmouth bass was sampled in a gillnet, marking the first time a smallmouth has been sampled by DNR gear. Anglers report occasional catches of smallmouth bass around Bear and Pelican Islands. To promote and maintain a healthy fish population, pollution and other inputs need to be controlled. Fish habitat is directly affected by water quality. Nutrient, sediment and other waste inputs can drastically alter the chemical and physical components of Leech Lake. Best management practices should be employed when developing a shoreline. Careless development within the watershed and the loss of upland and aquatic vegetation can accelerate the natural aging of a lake. It is paramount to maintain the current water quality of Leech Lake through watershed management to preserve this fishery for future generations to enjoy.

WALLEYE: The 1997 catch of walleye per experimental gillnet lift was 5.7 (Table 1). This catch was lower than the 1996 catch (9.5/lift) but within the range of values experienced since annual sampling of Leech Lake began (1983). Historically, catch rates have ranged from 13.4/lift (1988) to 4.6/lift (1993; Table 2). The predicted near record walleye catch rate for 1997 was not realized. Possible explanations include: 1) High water clarity may have caused walleye to use areas of the lake not sampled. 2) Yellow perch experienced excellent reproduction that increased food availability and may have lessened travel needed to obtain food.This would reduce the probability of encountering a gillnet. 3) Increased mortality reduced numbers of walleye present in the lake.Examination of the length frequency distribution showed fewer walleye were sampled throughout the distribution and not just the components subjected to exploitation (Table 5). Considering the consistency of walleye reproduction since 1994, it appears environmental factors influenced walleye catch rates and not increased mortality. Preliminary indications are; the 1994 and 1995 walleye year classes continue to comprise a large percentage of sampled walleye. The 1996 year class is also well represented. Because of growth of walleye from the 1994 and 1995 year classes, average length and weight have increased from the record low values in 1996 (13.1 inches and 0.9 pounds) to 13.9 inches and 1.1 pounds (Table 1). Average length and weight should continue to increase until the next large year class is recruited to the gillnet.In 1997, Leech Lake anglers and resort owners reported good walleye angling during the open water season. Some concern was expressed regarding the lack of 2-pound walleye and the large numbers of relatively small walleye. In 1995 and 1996, just the opposite was true. Anglers were concerned about few small walleye being caught. Both events were a result of poor recruitment of the 1992 and 1993 year classes. Reproduction was good in 1992, but a shortage of food caused both year classes to experience high mortality and poor recruitment.Although a large yellow perch hatch in 1997 may slow angling success in 1998, especially during midsummer, anglers can expect good walleye action. The 1994 and 1995 year classes are acceptable to anglers and present in large numbers. Near mid-August, the 1996 year class will also begin to be large enough for anglers to harvest. These three year classes coupled with 1988 and 1991 year-classes will provide good walleye angling opportunities for years to come on Leech Lake.NORTHERN PIKE: The 1997 catch of northern pike per experimental gill net set was 5.1 (Table 1). This catch rate was higher than the 1983-1997 average (4.7 northern pike per set). Sampled northern pike averaged 21.0 inches and 2.4 pounds and was similar to the 1983-1997 average (21.1 inches and 2.3 pounds). Of the 180 northern pike sampled, 62 percent were female and 38 percent were male (Table 6). Northern pike angling was again reported to be good this past year. During the International Muskellunge Tournament held in early September, more northern pike larger than 36 inches were reported from Leech Lake than all other lakes. YELLOW PERCH: The 1997 catch of yellow perch per experimental gill net set was 32.1 (Table 1). This catch was the third highest since the large lake program began (1983). The lowest catch occurred in 1986 (13.2 yellow perch per set) and the highest in 1995 (37.7 yellow perch per set; Table 2). The 1997 average length of sampled yellow perch was 7.5 inches. This average declined for the first time since 1992. Recruitment to the gillnet of a strong year class was responsible for the decline in 1992 and likely will be responsible for the decline in 1997. This will be determined once age and growth data are analyzed. As in most previous sampling, the average weight of sampled yellow perch was 0.2 pounds. No year has deviated more than 0.1 pounds from this average. Sex was determined for 1006 of the 1124 yellow perch sampled (Table 6). Of those, 60% were females and 40% were males. Female yellow perch have consistently outnumbered males because of gill net selectivity for female yellow perch. Anglers enjoyed good success while angling for yellow perch this past year. Best success occurred from opening of fishing to mid-June and from mid-August to near freeze-up. Local conservation officers reported seeing good yellow perch success from mid-August to near freeze-up. Humans have had dramatic impacts on fish populations by altering habitats necessary for successful reproduction, growth, and survival. In particular, lakeshores are highly sensitive areas that are vital to the overall health of our lakes. Terrestrial vegetation provides habitat for birds, mammals, and amphibians and buffers lakes from runoff that carry chemicals and sediment. Near-shore areas provide protection and food for the early life-stages of some species, such as walleye, and serve as year-round habitat for others, such as bluegill and largemouth bass. Any changes that have a negative effect on these areas will adversely impact the fishery. Therefore, protection of these sensitive areas is paramount to ensuring the sustainability and quality of Minnesota's precious water resources for future generations.

Action plan objectives were to increase the relative abundance and to stabilize the population size structure of these two species. The annual fishery survey using experimental gill nets was completed by the Walker Area Fisheries office, MN DNR, between 7 September and 18 September 2009. Walleye: Since the Large Lake Program began in 1983, walleye gillnet catch rates have ranged from 4.6 fish/net (1993) to 13.4 fish/net (1988). The 2009 catch of walleye per experimental gillnet set was 8.61 fish/net and remains above the 1983-2009 average of 7.6 fish/net. The increase in the walleye gillnet catch rate is due to the large year classes of walleyes produced during 2005, 2006, and 2007; 79% of walleye caught during the 2009 gillnet survey were from these three year classes. Northern pike gillnet catch rates have remained relatively stable since 1983, ranging from 3.6 fish/net (1993) to 6.2 fish/net (1995) with an average of 4.8 fish/net. Northern pike captured in 2009 gillnet sets ranged in length from 11 to 32 inches.

Muskellunge: Only one muskellunge was sampled in experimental gillnet sets during 2009. Muskellunge are typically low in abundance and exceed sizes that are effectively sampled with gillnets.

Muskie anglers averaged 0.013 fish/hour, or 1 fish/100 angler-hours, during the 2009 fishing season. This is lower than the average for targeting anglers (0.018 fish/hour), but and is higher than the 2004-2005 average (0.009 fish/hour) and still within the range of normal. In contrast to 2008, muskie anglers tended to catch fish more frequently in the main lake (0.020 fish/hour) than in the western bays (0.005 fish/hour) and were most successful during August and September.

In cooperation with various Muskies Inc. chapters and other anglers, the Minnesota Department of Natural Resources will begin efforts to estimate the size of the muskellunge population. Anglers will be asked to collect scale samples and other information from muskies they catch while fishing Leech Lake during 2009-2010. Yellow Perch: Gillnet catch rates of yellow perch have ranged from 12.9 fish/net (2005) to 37.7 fish/net (1995). The 2009 catch rate of yellow perch in experimental gillnet sets was 25.8 fish/net. This is above the 1983-2009 average of 22.0 fish/net. Yellow perch sampled in 2009 gillnet sets ranged in length from 5 inches to 12 inches. Of the total perch caught, 33% were 8 inches and longer and 11% were 10 inches and longer; both of these proportions have increased during recent years.

Anglers targeting yellow perch averaged a catch rate of 5.892 perch/hour and a harvest rate of 2.020 perch/hour during 2009. Catch and harvest rates were highest during September.

Cisco: The 2009 catch rate of cisco per experimental gillnet set was 11.9 fish/net, well above the long-term average of 5.65 fish/net and the highest observation since 1987. Gillnet catch rates of cisco have varied considerable, ranging from 0.6 fish/net (2006) to 18.5 fish/net (1987). Leech Lake is the third largest lake entirely within the boundaries of Minnesota and has approximately 112,000 surface acres. The lake is geographically located in three glacial zones and has an irregular shape with many large and small bays. The deepest area of the lake is located in Walker Bay where depths reach around 150 feet deep. Approximately 80% of the lake is less than 35 feet deep. Similar to other large lakes in Minnesota, the fish community is dominated by species in the perch and pike families. Walleye, northern pike, and muskellunge are the primary predator species, while yellow perch and cisco serve as the principal forage. Leech Lake is well known among anglers as a tremendous multi-species fishery, including excellent fishing opportunities for walleye, yellow perch, northern pike, muskellunge, largemouth bass, sunfish, and black crappie.

Leech Lake has been surveyed annually with standardized assessments since 1983. Establishment of long-term data sets on Leech Lake and Minnesota's other large walleye lakes allow biologists to compare current observations against historical averages. These long-term data sets can also provide insight into other lakes having similar physical and biological properties that are not sampled as frequently. Population metrics for a particular species, such as the highs and lows in gill net catch rates or the growth rates of fish, are constantly changing as they move from one extreme of their observed normal range to the other, much like a pendulum. While highs and lows are normal and rarely sustained past one year, consecutive observations at either extreme can be indicative of changes to an ecosystem. These may include exotic species introductions, shifts in habitat availability and/or quality, beneficial or adverse environmental conditions, and increased or decreased competition for resources between species or among year classes of the same species or among several species with similar requirements. Regardless, it is important to remember that all populations of flora and fauna fluctuate dramatically and that this natural variability is strongly influenced by the changing environment in which they live as well as the other species of plants and animals they share it with.

The MN DNR convened a citizen input committee (Leech Lake Advisory Committee; LLAC) comprised of stakeholders representing local and statewide interests in Leech Lake management. This group outlined walleye population management objectives and actions, including double-crested cormorant control, the walleye regulation, and walleye fry stocking (LLAC 2010). These recommendations were incorporated into DNR's Leech Lake Management Plan, 2011-2015 (Schultz 2010a). These management goals, where appropriate, are referenced in this report.

The current protected slot walleye regulation (PSL) on Leech Lake (18-26" walleye must be immediately released; possession limit of 4, one of which may be longer than 26") was reviewed and compared to other regulation options (Schultz and Staples 2010a). Public comment on proposed regulation changes was solicited during October, 2010. The majority of public input supported maintaining the regulation through 2015, though some comments expressed consideration for a more liberal length limit that adjusts with measures of spawner biomass. Therefore, if measures of spawner biomass exceed 2.0 lbs/acre during two consecutive years, DNR will consider adjusting the regulation to a 20-26" PSL, bag of 4, one fish over 26" allowed in possession to begin the ensuing season based on current information.

Aquatic invasive species currently found in Leech Lake include rusty crayfish, heterosporosis, curly-leaf pondweed, Eurasian watermilfoil, purple loosestrife, and banded mystery snail. Currently invasive plant species are not widely distributed within Leech Lake. Other aquatic invasive species are increasing in prevalence throughout Minnesota and pose a likely risk. Anglers and boaters alike are encouraged to review and adhere to rules requiring proper bait disposal, draining all water from bait containers, livewells, bilge, and the watercraft, and properly inspecting and removing all plants and animals from the watercraft, anchor, and trailer when leaving a lake. Information on invasive species issues and prevention can be found at www.dnr.state.mn.us/invasives/index_aquatic/.

Northern pike gillnet catch rates have remained relatively stable since 1983, ranging from 3.6 fish/net (1993) to 6.2 fish/net (1995) with an average of 4.8 fish/net. Northern pike captured in 2016 gillnet sets ranged in length from 9 to 35 inches.

Muskellunge: Muskellunge from Miller Bay near Whipholt are currently collected and spawned for the statewide broodstock program every four years, with spawning operations most recently occurring in 2013. A total of 51 individual fish were captured in May of 2013, of which 23 were female and 28 were male. Females ranged in length from 39-53 inches, while males ranged from 31-46 inches.

Yellow Perch: Catch rates in 2016 were 9.4 (fish/net), lower than the long-term average of 20.7(fish/net) and was a record low. Previous catch rates ranged from 12.1 fish/net (2013) to 37.7 fish/net (1995). Total length of Yellow Perch sampled ranged from 5 to nearly 13 inches and ages ranged from 2 to 12 years old. The 2011, 2012, and 2013 year classes made up 84% of all Yellow Perch sampled.

Cisco: The overall catch rate was 7.8 fish/net. Cisco catch rates (fish/net) have increased the last 4 years and are above the long-term average (5.4 fish/net). Previous catch rates ranged from 0.6 fish/net (2006) to 18.5 fish/net (1987). Cisco sampled ranged from 4 to 19 inches. Eleven year classes were represented in the 2016 sample, with the 2014 and 2015 year classes most abundant. Warmer summers causing summer kills have likely been the source of cisco catch rates remaining relatively low since 1995. However, no significant summer kill events have been observed during the past four years. Lengths of cisco sampled ranged from 5 to 18 inches. Within the Leech Lake Indian Reservation the Whitefish limit is 25 and the Cisco (Tullibee) limit is 50, which is an exception to the statewide regulation. Daily and possession limits are the same.

Status of the Fishery (as of 2/27/2020)

Leech Lake is the third largest lake entirely within the boundaries of Minnesota and has approximately 112,000 surface acres. The lake has an irregular shape with a variety of large and small bays. The deepest area of the lake is located in Walker Bay where depths approach 160 feet deep. Approximately 80% of the lake is less than 35 feet deep. Walleye, Northern Pike, and Muskellunge are the primary predator species, while Yellow Perch and Tullibee (Cisco) serve as the principal forage. Leech Lake is well known among anglers as a tremendous multi-species fishery, and includes excellent fishing opportunities for Walleye, Yellow Perch, Northern Pike, Muskellunge, Largemouth Bass, Sunfish, and Black Crappie.

The MN DNR convened a citizen input committee (Leech Lake Fisheries Input Group; LLFIG) comprised of 16 stakeholders representing local and statewide interests in Leech Lake management. This group assisted the MN DNR in developing a list of sportfish population goals, objectives, and management actions. These recommendations were incorporated into the DNR's 2016-2020 Fisheries Management Plan for Leech Lake.

The Walleye regulation on Leech Lake was changed to a 4 fish possession limit with no more than 1 Walleye over 20" allowed in possession, effective May 11, 2019. The objectives of this regulation change was to reduce spawner stock biomass and provide additional harvest opportunity to anglers. The regulation will be evaluated annually and adjustments will be made based on management plan objectives and action items.

Updates on specific species are provided below:

Walleye: Since the current sampling plan that began in 1983, Walleye gillnet catch rates have ranged from 4.6 fish/net (1993) to 13.4 fish/net (1988). The 2019 catch rate was 8.6 fish/net which was similar to the1983-2019 average catch rate (8.1 fish/net) and within the management objectives of 7-10 fish/net. Walleye sampled in gillnets ranged in length from 6 to 28 inches, and included a number of younger year classes that should be large enough to harvest in the next year or two. Twenty five percent of the Walleye in the 2019 sample were over 20 inches.

Northern Pike: The gillnet catch rate of Northern Pike was 4.9 fish/net. Northern Pike gillnet catch rates have remained relatively stable since 1983, ranging from 3.6 fish/net (1993) to 6.2 fish/net (1995) with an average of 4.8 fish/net. Northern Pike ranged in length from 9 to 36 inches. There is a 10 fish possession limit with none allowed in the 22-26" PSL and only 2 over 26" allowed in possession.

Muskellunge: Since 2015, the MNDNR has worked with Muskellunge tournament participants on Leech Lake to collect creel information. In 2019, the DNR obtained creel interviews from 164 anglers from 3 tournaments. Information on hours fished, the number and size of fish that were caught was collected. Lengths of tournament Muskellunge caught on Leech ranged from 22 to 50 inches and the average time it took tournament anglers to catch a Muskellunge was 48 hours. There is a 54" minimum size limit with only 1 allowed in possession.

Yellow Perch: Gill net catch rates were 16.1 (fish/net), up from 10.2 fish/net in 2018. Historical catch rates have ranged from 9.4 fish/net (2016) to 37.7 fish/net (1995). Yellow Perch sampled ranged from 5 to 11 inches with nearly 30 percent of fish over 8.0 inches.

Tullibee (Cisco): The gill net catch rate was 3.0 fish/net, which was below the long-term average (5.4 fish/net). Catch rates have ranged from 0.6 fish/net (2006) to 18.5 fish/net (1987). Tullibee sampled ranged from 7 to 17 inches. Warmer summers causing summer kills have likely been the source of Tullibee catch rates remaining relatively low since 1995. However, no significant summer kill events have been observed during the past five years. Within the Leech Lake Reservation the Whitefish limit is 25 and the Tullibee (Cisco) limit is 50, which is an exception to the statewide regulation. Daily and possession limits are the same.

Bass: A Largemouth Bass, Bluegill, and Black Crappie assessment occurred during the springs of 2012, 2015, and 2018. Catch rates for Largemouth Bass ? 15 inches were similar among years (range: 3 to 6 fish/hour). Lengths in 2018 ranged from 3 to 19 inches. Anglers can find quality bass fishing opportunities in the beds of mixed vegetation in most major bays. Smallmouth Bass have always been present but are infrequently sampled or caught by anglers. Their population density is low and they are not well-distributed throughout the lake at this time.

Bluegill: Spring electrofishing catch rates for all Bluegill (30 fish/hour) were lower than the 2015 (47 fish/hour) and 2012 (33 fish/hour) catch rates. Size quality is high with lengths sampled in 2018 ranging from 2 to 10 inches; 20 percent of the Bluegill sampled were over 8 inches.

Black Crappie: Spring electrofishing catch rates for all Black Crappie were 4 fish/hour in 2018, compared to 9 fish/hour in 2015 and 5 fish/hour in 2012. Lengths in 2018 ranged from 4 to 14 inches and 44 percent were 10 inches or longer.

Aquatic invasive species currently found in Leech Lake include Rusty Crayfish, Heterosporosis, Curly-Leaf Pondweed, Eurasian Watermilfoil, Purple Loosestrife, Zebra Mussels, and Banded Mystery Snails. Eurasian Watermilfoil has established in open-water areas of the lake. Other aquatic invasive species such as Spiny Waterfleas are increasing in prevalence throughout Minnesota and pose a likely risk but have not been found in Leech Lake to date. Anglers and boaters alike are encouraged to review and adhere to rules requiring proper bait disposal, draining all water from bait containers, livewells, bilge, and the watercraft, and properly inspecting and removing all plants and animals from the watercraft, anchor, and trailer when leaving a lake. Information on invasive species issues and prevention can be found by searching MNDNR invasive species in your preferred internet search engine or by calling your local DNR office.
